This code first creates a list `perfect_squares` to store the number of perfect squares for each value up to `n`. Then it iterates over the list, checking if each value is a perfect square. If it is, it sets the corresponding value in `perfect_squares` to 1. Otherwise, it finds the largest perfect square less than or equal to the current value and updates the corresponding value in `perfect_squares` accordingly. Finally, it returns the value of `perfect_squares[n]`, which represents the length of the smallest list of perfect squares that add up to `n`.

Note that this code has a time complexity of O(n^(3/2)) due to the use of a square root operation inside a loop. However, it should be able to handle the given test cases within the time limit.

